<div class="sec-label">Profile</div>

<div class="bio-card">
  I am a <strong>Computer Science MSc student at the Jagiellonian University in Kraków</strong>,
  where I previously completed my BSc. My academic path is deliberately interdisciplinary —
  an earlier BSc in Economics at the University of Warsaw gave me a foundation in quantitative
  reasoning before I committed fully to CS.
</div>
<div class="bio-card">
  My core research focus is <strong>applied machine learning in medicine and biology</strong> —
  problems that require bridging multiple domains simultaneously. Building a working ECG classifier
  means understanding both signal processing and deep learning; predicting ADMET drug profiles
  requires knowledge of chemistry, biology, and multi-task learning architecture.
</div>
<div class="hbox">
  <strong>Current focus:</strong> ADMET property prediction using multi-task learning (MTL) as part
  of the ML in Drug Design course at GMUM / Jagiellonian University. Exploring how shared
  representations across pharmacokinetic endpoints improve data efficiency and generalization.
</div>
<div class="bio-card">
  Before and alongside my CS studies I have worked in <strong>IT support and network
  engineering</strong> in the United States — VoIP systems, VLAN segmentation, server administration
  and complete network overhauls for a financial firm in Connecticut.
</div>
<div class="bio-card">
  I write primarily in <strong>Python, C++, and Java</strong>, with significant work in Swift
  (iOS / CoreML) and C# (Godot, .NET). I approach software with an emphasis on correctness and
  clean architecture.
</div>

